\begin_layout Standard
Pickleball is a cross between tennis, badminton, and ping-pong.
 It is played with a thick plastic ball, wood or plastic paddles, and a
 low net.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like most racquet sports, pickleball is all about using your paddle to keep
 the ball moving back and forth in a controlled sequence.
 The ball can only bounce once on each side of the court.
 Under certain circumstances, you can also 
\emph on
volley, 
\emph default
hitting the ball before it bounces on your side of the court.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a player breaks the sequence, such as by hitting the ball into the
 net, letting it bounce twice in a row, or sending it out of bounds, he/she
 has committed a 
\emph on
fault 
\emph default
(also called an 
\emph on
error.
\emph default
) The time from when the ball is 
\emph on
served
\emph default
 (set in motion) to the time a fault is committed is called a 
\emph on
rally.

\emph default
 If you fault, either the other team will gain points or you/your team will
 lose the opportunity to serve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Serving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All serves must be underhand, and from behind the baseline with at least
 one foot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Serves must be cross-court diagonally and land within the appropriate 
\emph on
service box
\emph default
.
 The baseline, sidelines, and center line are considered 
\emph on
in
\emph default
.
 The kitchen line is considered 
\emph on
out
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You only have one attempt per rally to make a successful serve, unless there
 is a 
\emph on
let
\emph default
.
 A let is when the ball touches the net on the serve and still lands in
 the correct service box.
 In this case, the server must try again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The singles serving sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In singles, the serving player will serve from the right court when their
 score is even, and from the left court when their score is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The doubles serving sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The serving sequence ensures each player on a doubles court has a fair opportuni
ty to serve from both halves of the court.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once a team gains possession of the ball, the first serve is made by the
 player on the right.
 This is Server 1.
 They must serve to the opposing team's right court.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the receiving team faults, the serving teammates switch sides of the
 court.
 Server 1 must now send the ball to the opposing team's left court.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Server 1 will continue to serve until he/she commits a fault.

\emph on
 
\emph default
In this case, their teammate, Server 2, gets the ball.
 
\emph on

